 inspired this post. Yesterday I was browsing for a Deep Q Learning implementation in TensorFlow (to see how others deal with computing the numpy equivalent of Q[:, a], where a is an integer vector — turns out this trivial operation is not supported in TF). Anyway, I searched “dqn tensorflow”, clicked the first link, and found the core code. Here is an excerpt:","hasDropCap":null,"dropCapImage":null,"markups":[{"__typename":"Markup","type":"STRONG","start":205,"end":212,"href":null,"anchorType":null,"userId":null,"linkMetadata":null},{"__typename":"Markup","type":"STRONG","start":220,"end":221,"href":null,"anchorType":null,"userId":null,"linkMetadata":null},{"__typename":"Markup","type":"EM","start":322,"end":338,"href":null,"anchorType":null,"userId":null,"linkMetadata":null}],"codeBlockMetadata":null,"iframe":null,"mixtapeMetadata":null},"ImageMetadata:1*pyz5lHFDho07cFzIA6tWmQ.png":{"__typename":"ImageMetadata","id":"1*pyz5lHFDho07cFzIA6tWmQ.png","originalHeight":243,"originalWidth":960,"focusPercentX":null,"focusPercentY":null,"alt":null},"Paragraph:6dbb6fdc0768_28":{"__typename":"Paragraph","id":"6dbb6fdc0768_28","name":"d44b","type":"IMG","href":null,"layout":"INSET_CENTER","metadata":{"__ref":"ImageMetadata:1*pyz5lHFDho07cFzIA6tWmQ.png"},"text":"","hasDropCap":null,"dropCapImage":null,"markups":[],"codeBlockMetadata":null,"iframe":null,"mixtapeMetadata":null},"Paragraph:6dbb6fdc0768_29":{"__typename":"Paragraph","id":"6dbb6fdc0768_29","name":"439c","type":"P","href":null,"layout":null,"metadata":null,"text":"If you’re familiar with DQN, you can see that there is the target_q_t, which is just [reward * \\gamma \\argmax_a Q(s’,a)], and then there is q_acted, which is Q(s,a) of the action that was taken. The authors here subtract the two into variable delta, which they then want to minimize on line 295 with the L2 loss with tf.reduce_mean(tf.square()). So far so good.","hasDropCap":null,"dropCapImage":null,"markups":[{"__typename":"Markup","type":"STRONG","start"